🔹 Problem: Top K Frequent Elements
Given an integer array nums and an integer k, return the k most frequent elements.

👉 Example:
Input: nums = [1,1,1,2,2,3], k = 2
Output: [1,2]

🧠 1. Brute Force Approach
💡 Idea:
Count frequency
Repeatedly find max frequency element k times

⏱ Complexity:
Time: O(n * k) or worse (if scanning repeatedly)
Space: O(n)

✅ Code:
vector<int> topKFrequent(vector<int>& nums, int k) {
    unordered_map<int, int> freq;
    for(int num : nums) freq[num]++;

    vector<int> result;

    for(int i = 0; i < k; i++) {
        int maxFreq = -1, element;

        for(auto& it : freq) {
            if(it.second > maxFreq) {
                maxFreq = it.second;
                element = it.first;
            }
        }

        result.push_back(element);
        freq[element] = -1; // mark used
    }

    return result;
}

❌ Cons:
Inefficient (re-scans map multiple times)
Doesn’t scale well
Not interview-preferred

📌 When to use:
Just to explain baseline thinking


⚡ 2. Better Approach (Sorting by Frequency)
💡 Idea:
Count frequencies
Store in vector
Sort by frequency (descending)

⏱ Complexity:
Time: O(n log n)
Space: O(n)

✅ Code:
vector<int> topKFrequent(vector<int>& nums, int k) {
    unordered_map<int, int> freq;
    for(int num : nums) freq[num]++;

    vector<pair<int,int>> arr(freq.begin(), freq.end());

    sort(arr.begin(), arr.end(), [](auto& a, auto& b) {
        return a.second > b.second;
    });

    vector<int> result;
    for(int i = 0; i < k; i++) {
        result.push_back(arr[i].first);
    }

    return result;
}

❌ Cons:
Sorting all elements is unnecessary
Slower than optimal for large input
Doesn’t exploit the “top k” nature efficiently

📌 When to use:
Simple and readable
Acceptable if constraints are moderate


🚀 3. Optimal Approach (Min Heap)
💡 Idea:
Keep a min heap of size k
Store {frequency, element}
Remove smallest when size > k

⏱ Complexity:
Time: O(n log k)
Space: O(n)

✅ Code:
vector<int> topKFrequent(vector<int>& nums, int k) {
    unordered_map<int, int> freq;
    for(int num : nums) freq[num]++;

    priority_queue<pair<int,int>, vector<pair<int,int>>, greater<>> minHeap;

    for(auto& it : freq) {
        minHeap.push({it.second, it.first});
        if(minHeap.size() > k) {
            minHeap.pop();
        }
    }

    vector<int> result;
    while(!minHeap.empty()) {
        result.push_back(minHeap.top().second);
        minHeap.pop();
    }

    return result;
}

❌ Cons:
Slightly complex to write
Heap operations overhead
Not strictly O(n)

📌 When to use:
When k << n (very efficient)
Most practical optimal solution

🚀🚀 4. Best Optimal (Bucket Sort)
💡 Idea:
Frequency range is 1 → n
Create buckets where index = frequency
Put elements into corresponding buckets

⏱ Complexity:
Time: O(n) ✅
Space: O(n)

✅ Code:
vector<int> topKFrequent(vector<int>& nums, int k) {
    unordered_map<int, int> freq;
    for(int num : nums) freq[num]++;

    vector<vector<int>> bucket(nums.size() + 1);

    for(auto& it : freq) {
        bucket[it.second].push_back(it.first);
    }

    vector<int> result;

    for(int i = bucket.size() - 1; i >= 0 && result.size() < k; i--) {
        for(int num : bucket[i]) {
            result.push_back(num);
            if(result.size() == k) break;
        }
    }

    return result;
}

❌ Cons:
Less intuitive
Uses extra memory (bucket array)
Slightly harder to explain

📌 When to use:
When the interviewer asks for O(n) solution
When constraints are large
